The '''Booksellers's Bill''' was a 1774 [[bill (proposed law)|bill]] introduced into the [[Parliament of Great Britain]] in the wake of the important [[copyright]] case of ''[[Donaldson v. Beckett]]''.
In ''Donaldson'' a perpetual [[common law copyright]] was denied to booksellers and it was held that copyright was a creation of [[statute]] and could be limited in its [[Copyright term|duration]]. As a result, booksellers sought to have the duration of their copyright extended to 14 years. Under [[Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom#Stages of a bill|UK parliamentary procedure]], the bill passed the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] but was defeated in the [[House of Lords]] and never became an [[act of parliament]].
