{{Civil procedure (United States)}}
In U.S. [[legal procedure]], each party to a [[lawsuit]] has the duty to disclose certain information, such as the names and addresses of [[witness]]es, and copies of any documents that it intends to use as evidence, to the opposing party.  This duty is subject to certain exceptions, as outlined in the ''[[Federal Rules of Civil Procedure]]''; furthermore, the rules applicable in [[State court (United States)|state courts]] vary from state to state.

In [[United States patent law]], during [[patent prosecution]], an applicant has a duty to disclose all information [[materiality (law)|material]] to [[patentability]]. Breach of this duty can lead to a holding of [[inequitable conduct]], in which case the patent is unenforceable.<ref>[https://www.uspto.gov/web/offices/pac/mpep/mpep-9020-appx-r.html#aia_d0e319407 37 C.F.R. § 1.56]</ref>

