{{Crystal}} An independent [[electoral commission]] is planned by [[Government of the 32nd Dáil|the current Irish government]] to oversee the conduct of [[elections in the Republic of Ireland|all elections in the state]]. This responsibility is at present distributed among various [[Department of State (Ireland)|government departments]], statutory agencies and components of the [[Oireachtas]] (parliament).
==History== An electoral commission was recommended by several official reports, including the Second Report (2006) of the [[Electronic voting in Ireland|Commission on Electronic Voting]].<ref name="evoting2p206">{{cite book|author=Commission on Electronic Voting|title=Second Report; on the Secrecy, Accuracy and Testing of the Chosen Electronic Voting System|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/Data/Library3/Library2/DL001570.pdf#page=208 |format=PDF|date=July 2006|publisher=Stationery Office|location=Dublin|page=206, R.41 }}</ref> [[Private member's bill]]s to establish an electoral commission were introduced by [[Ciarán Lynch]] in 2008 and 2012.<ref> * {{cite web |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/viewdoc.asp?fn=/documents/bills28/bills/2008/2608/document1.htm |title=Electoral Commission Bill 2008 (PMB) — Bill Number 26 of 2008 |work=Bills |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=27 November 2017}} * {{cite web |url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/viewdoc.asp?fn=/documents/bills28/bills/2012/10012/document1.htm |title=Electoral Commission Bill 2012 (PMB) — Bill Number 100 of 2012 |work=Bills |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=27 November 2017}} </ref>
In 2008, the then [[Department of the Environment, Heritage and Local Government]] commissioned and published a study on introducing an electoral commission, carried out by academics from [[University College Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.environ.ie/en/LocalGovernment/Voting/PublicationsDocuments/FileDownLoad,19472,en.pdf |title=Preliminary study on the establishment of an Electoral Commission in Ireland |last=Sinnott |first=Richard |author2=John Coakley |author3=John O’Dowd |author4=James McBride |date=November 2008 |publisher=[[Department of the Environment, Heritage and Local Government]] |accessdate=28 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125051127/http://www.environ.ie/en/LocalGovernment/Voting/PublicationsDocuments/FileDownLoad,19472,en.pdf |archivedate=25 November 2013 |df= }}</ref> After the [[Irish general election, 2011|2011 general election]], the [[Fine Gael]] and [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour]] parties formed [[Government of the 31st Dáil|a coalition government]] whose programme included a commitment to establish an electoral commission.<ref>DECLG 2015, p.5</ref> Such a commission was also recommended in the [[Constitutional Convention (Ireland)|Constitutional Convention]]'s 2013 report on the system of elections to [[Dáil Éireann]] (lower house of the Oireachtas),<ref>Constitutional Convention 2013, p.9</ref> which was also endorsed the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/takes/dail2014121800047#N4|title=Fourth Report of the Constitutional Convention on the Dáil Electoral System: Statements (Continued)|date=18 December 2014|work=Dáil Éireann debates|page=47|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]], the [[Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]], outlined progress of the plan in [[Seanad Éireann]] (upper house of the Oireachtas) in December 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/Speeches/%E2%80%9CProgress_on_the_Establishment_of_Independent_Electoral_Commission%E2%80%9D_Speech_by_the_Minister_for_the_Environment_Community_and_Local_Government_Alan_Kelly_T_D_.html|title="Progress on the Establishment of Independent Electoral Commission" Speech by the Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government, Alan Kelly T.D.|date=17 December 2014|work=MerrionStreet.ie|publisher=[[Government of Ireland]]|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/takes/seanad2014121700024#BB00300 |title=Electoral Commission: Motion |date=17 December 2014 |work=Seanad Éireann debates |page=24 |accessdate=28 April 2015 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The government published a consultation paper in January 2015, and said it intended to introduce a [[bill (law)|bill]] in the Oireachtas in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/eng/Taoiseach_and_Government/Government_Legislation_Programme/Government_Legislative_Programme_Spring_Summer_2015.pdf#page=13 |format=PDF |title=Section C: Bills in respect of which heads have yet to be approved by Government|last=Kehoe|first=Paul|authorlink=Paul Kehoe|date=14 January 2015|work=Government Legislation Programme: Spring/Summer Session 2015 |page=13 |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The Oireachtas Joint Committee on Environment, Culture and the Gaeltacht discussed the plan with Alan Kelly on 10 March 2015. Kelly stated that drafting the enabling bill would begin when the committee had consulted and reported back to him, that he expected the bill to be enacted by the end of 2015, that the commission would not be established before the [[Irish general election, 2016|next general election]], and that functions should be assigned to it on a phased basis.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/Debates%20Authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015031000002|title=Electoral Commission: Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government|date=10 March 2015|work=Joint Committee on Environment, Culture and the Gaeltacht proceedings|publisher=Oireachtas|accessdate=22 May 2015}} </ref> In April 2015 the committee invited submissions on the government's consultation paper from interest groups,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/parliament/mediazone/pressreleases/2015/name-28003-en.html|title=Have your say: Environment Committee seeks submissions on Electoral Commission |author=Joint Committee on Environment, Culture and the Gaeltacht |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> and held hearings with them in June and July.<ref> Joint Committee on Environment, Culture and the Gaeltacht ''Electoral Commission in Ireland: Discussion''; [http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/Debates%20Authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015061600002?opendocument#B00050 16 June 2015] [http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/Debates%20Authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015062300002?opendocument#C00100 23 June 2015] [http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015063000002?opendocument#B00100 30 June 2015] [http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015070700002?opendocument#A00100 7 July 2015] [http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/committeetakes/ENJ2015071400002?opendocument#A00100 14 July 2015] </ref> The committee's report was launched on 14 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/viewdoc.asp?fn=/documents/thisweek/business-2016/document2.htm|title=11–15 January 2016|date=January 2016|work=This Week in the Houses of the Oireachtas|publisher=Oireachtas|accessdate=12 January 2016 |quote=Report Launch / Report on the Consultation on the Proposed Electoral Commission 2016 /Joint Committee on Environment, Culture and the Gaeltacht / Audio Visual Room, LH2000, on Thursday, 14 January 2016 at 11 a.m. }}</ref>
After the [[Irish general election, 2016|2016 general election]], a [[Government of the 32nd Dáil|minority coalition government]] was formed by Fine Gael and [[independent politician|independent]]s with [[confidence and supply]] support from [[Fianna Fáil]]. Its programme commits to establishing an electoral commission "independent of Government and directly accountable to the Oireachtas".<ref name="Programme_for_Partnership_Government">{{cite web|url=http://www.merrionstreet.ie/MerrionStreet/en/ImageLibrary/Programme_for_Partnership_Government.pdf#page=153 |format=PDF|title=A Programme for a Partnership Government|date=11 May 2016|publisher=Government of Ireland|pages=152–3|accessdate=3 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kildarestreet.com/wrans/?id=2016-07-05a.663|title=Written answers: Electoral Commission Establishment |last=Coveney|first=Simon|date=5 Jul 2016|work=Dáil debates|publisher=KildareStreet.com|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> The government's September 2016 list of planned legislation includes the Electoral Commission Bill in the [[Department of Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government]]'s "medium and long term" plans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merrionstreet.ie/MerrionStreet/en/ImageLibrary/20160927_Legislation_Programme_Autumn_Session_2016.pdf|title=Legislation Programme Autumn 2016 |date=27 September 2016 |publisher=Office of the Government Chief Whip|pages=6, 24|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> In June 2017, the Department was preparing a [[Regulatory Impact Analysis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kildarestreet.com/wrans/?id=2017-07-13a.3433|title=Electoral Commission Establishment|date=13 Jul 2017|work=Written answers|publisher=KildareStreet.com|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, Taoiseach [[Leo Varadkar]] said there was "no timeframe" for establishing the commission and it was "very much a long-term project".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kildarestreet.com/debates/?id=2017-10-04a.74#g119|title=Questions on Promised Legislation|date=4 Oct 2017|work=Dáil debates|publisher=KildareStreet.com|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>
==Possible functions== The Constitutional Convention took the [[Australian Electoral Commission]] and [[UK Electoral Commission]] as case studies of possible models for the Irish body.<ref>Constitutional Convention 2013, pp.62–63, 77</ref> The various official reports list functions which might be performed by the commission, and notes who is currently responsible for them.
